  "text": "The statement is incorrect.\n\\nWhile the first part is true - a total return swap (TRS) can be used as a financing tool - the second part is false in the most common financing structure.\n\\nWhen a TRS is used for financing, it is typically structured as a 'funded swap' or 'synthetic repo'. In this arrangement, the company seeking financing legally sells the reference asset to the financial institution (the swap provider) in exchange for cash. Simultaneously, they enter into a TRS where the company receives the total return of the asset (retaining economic exposure) and pays a financing rate to the institution.\n\\nBecause the financial institution has taken legal ownership of the asset at the start of the transaction, in the event of the company's default on its payment obligations, the institution already owns the underlying asset. It does not need to make a claim for it in bankruptcy proceedings as an unsecured creditor would. Therefore, the claim that 'the financial institution does not own the assets' in a default scenario is incorrect for this common financing application.",
  "is_correct": false
}
